Whenever I make public statements – no matter what I actually say – there follows a whole offensive tyranny on social media, where it calls for revocation, rejection of moderate politics, statements that I do not belong to the Labour Party.
That doesn't just happen to me.
In fact, I know that I have even had more luck than some of my colleagues, since the comments for me are, at least, mostly political in nature.
I can only admire the professionalism and purposefulness of those colleagues who face sexist or racist bribes every day without being afraid of them.
One of the biggest disappointments of this era in politics is how such insults became the norm.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said Labour should embrace a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that the party is far from widespread, with any sign of distrust or change in the rules of choice becoming increasingly tightened.
Over the past two years, I’ve received a lot of advice to tame myself, not to talk so much and then “everything will be okay”.
But that’s not why I came into politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student provoked by the Thatcher government, which by its neglect led to the literal breakdown of my excellent school, I have fought for better public services for those who need them most – whether as a local counselor or as a miner.
I have never hid my political views, including during the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could be confused in any way by my political stance and my disagreement with the current leadership.
To all those who supported the proposal on Friday, I would like to say that when the country rushes to Brexit, it will hurt households, businesses and the public sector, and I do not understand the desire to waste my time and energy in loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But my real message is not to the Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threats of withdrawal or political exclusion will refuse me to act in the way that I consider your best interests to be in your defense.
