John Edwards: Language Skills are Essential to Global Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, with this continuing in 2018 with another excellent presentation of exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports disciplines, arts, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen careers and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can compose and implement a personal curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language you understand about him, your words can reach him.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
The results of this year’s exams show that languages are among the most successful for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have achieved the high grade A.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS schools, showed that 72% of students achieved grade A in Chinese, with the same grade having 72% of German students, 69% of French schools and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need for the future.
Languages as a subject of free choice by students are currently receiving the same treatment as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) in both independent school programs and beyond.
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Labour Skills found that 17% indicated insufficient language skills due to employers having difficulty finding employees.
Therefore, it is becoming increasingly compulsory to speak foreign languages in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require the proficiency of a foreign language, which makes these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person masters a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill, which remains for a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multilingual person one breast in front of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adult citizens in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak a language, with French being the only language whose proficiency reaches a two-digit percentage with a rate of 15%.
That’s why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Mastering several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will be different from the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important to the UK in a future plan by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child has, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers being specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, there is no denying that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role for the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should really be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools.
