Students in Harvard on a course for enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year makes all students sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of learning “all night” using caffeine.
A professor found that students at the number one university in the world often don’t even think about the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keysler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women’s Hospital, designed the course, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“Finally, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me this only now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to students the most essential about how good sleep habits help academic and sporting achievements, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Bareira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is an image of a room in a dorm where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how sports achievements are affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of a sleep routine.
Another part of the participants was told how long-term sleep deprivation could increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe that they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” added Prof. Kiesler.
The culture of the pride of “learning all night long” still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Providing enough and quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says – even to avoid filling up, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in a mode of hunger that keeps them hungry.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Keysler prepare the course by taking one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He says his course “opened his eyes” and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Keysler recommends that students consider whether to set a sleep and wake alarm and know the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause problems.
