In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Burners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he said regarding the initiative.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own “online storage of personal data” or POD.
It contains lists, task lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It resembles Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, which are available through any browser, and at the same time is all of them at the same time.
The unique thing about the online storage of personal data is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it “entitlement to personal data.”
The idea for Inrupt, according to the company’s CEO John Bruce, is the company to invest resources, processes and appropriate skills to help Solid become accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Burners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers who signed a contract to work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Burners-Lee said he and his team did not talk to Facebook and Google about whether or not to make a complete change when all their business models were completely renewed overnight.
“We don’t want permission from them.”
In a publication in Medium on Saturday, Burners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s mission is to provide energy for trading and the ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the basis of Solid.
In 1994, Burners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Burners-Lee has had a strong influence in the debate over net neutrality.
Despite launching Inrupt, Burners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm extremely optimistic about this new era of the internet," Burners-Lee added.
Bernard Van: in memory of the priest, awarded with the Cross of Victoria during the First World War
The 100th anniversary is celebrated in the hometown of the only Anglican priest to be awarded the Cross of Victoria for his participation in hostilities during the First World War.
Lieutenant-Colonel Reverend Bernard Van won the prize on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper without realizing that he had been awarded the highest military honors in Britain.
A memorial was discovered on Saturday by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Van, said it was "extremely symbolic" that the monument was discovered exactly 100 years after his grandfather's medal-winning work.
According to the London Gazette on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy artillery and machine gun fire."
He later attacked the line of fire and with "incredible courage" led the building forward before attacking an artillery gun with one hand and killing three of the squad.
Lieutenant Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I know I could never do, but it makes me humble."
He and his brother, Dr. James Van, placed a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said it was a “great honor to participate in the parade” and added “the virtue of a true hero is demonstrated by the support that will be provided to many people.”
