Laverne Daley said he felt “less” than everyone else as he grew up because “it was not socially acceptable to like both girls and boys.”
He said, “To this day, the feeling of inferiority and being different from others are actually the things that give me the energy and the strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove that he was “something,” he said, so he wouldn’t disappoint anyone when he finally learned about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become an active participant in LGBT campaigns and is using his participation in this year’s British Community Games in Australia to call for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he is doing this because he is happy that he can live openly, without consequences, and wants to inspire “hope” in others.
The three-time world champion said that when he fell in love with a man - American director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 - he was "surprised."
