His son was named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father could not accept that he was going to die, and one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets to the 2012 London Olympics — because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You’re not going to be with me, Dad, not even on the front row,’” he said.
“I held his hand until I stopped breathing and at that moment, when I realized he was dead, I finally admitted he wasn’t invulnerable,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
“I just knew that my whole life I had dreamed of it – to jump at the Olympics in front of the audience at home. There was no more awesome feeling,” he said.
This also inspired the selection of his first song, "Proud" by Heather Small, which accompanied him during his preparations for the Olympics and still makes him cringe.
