Germany postpones launch of new warship
The newest frigate of the German fleet was due to be put into operation in 2014 to replace outdated warships from the Cold War, but this will not happen until at least next year due to malfunctioning systems and drastically rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the brand’s flagship of new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes an army spokesman.
The vessel was due to join the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships ordered by the fleet in 2007 will replace the outdated Bremen class frigates.
It is understandable that they will have a powerful gun, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer periods of maintenance – the newest frigates should be able to be used for up to two years before returning to the docking ports.
The continued delays mean, however, that the vanguard warships – which are said to allow Germany to demonstrate power across the ocean – will be old when they go into service.
The ill-fated frigate F125 entered the headlines last year when the German navy officially refused to put the vessel into operation and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of significant "software and hardware defects" that make the warship unusable if it is sent on a combat mission.
Software shortcomings are particularly important, as Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors – only half of the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship was significantly overloaded, reducing its efficiency and limiting the ability of the naval forces to add future upgrades.
The 7000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to be twice as heavy as the ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
