The official said the problem has become bigger over time as the old ships have been decommissioned, but no new ones have been provided.
He complained that no frigate of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the fleet.
The National Trust tracks the secret life of bats
A new study conducted at a mansion in the Scottish Mountains aims to establish how bats use the landscape when they hunt.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats, as well as the brown arrowhead water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key places in the mansion to track the activities of bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of call sounds of bats, as well as what species they emit.
A map of the habitat and a report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Duarte, NTS’s Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. creating meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Flea populations in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly over the past century.
They are endangered by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
Populations may be at risk from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their habits of hunting at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight paths.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 acres of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, inspections of asylums and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even created Scotland’s first and only special bat reserve at the Threave Manor in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Mansion manager David Thompson says it's the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have great terrain for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, a lot of mature trees and a completed suitable habitat.
But there’s a lot more about bats that’s not known, so the work we’re doing here and at other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed that it is important to check for the presence of bats before carrying out property maintenance activities, as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a shelter could kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Farrell, a Scottish employee at the Flea Trust, encouraged society to help.
She said, “I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, because we just don’t know what’s happening to their populations.”
