Fishing and farming are the foundations of the economy of the province of central Sulawesi, especially in the coastal area of the Dongala.
The extraction of nickel is also important for the province, but it is concentrated mainly in Morovali, on the opposite shore of Sulawesi.
Palu and Dongala have been overwhelmed several times by tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to data from the Indonesian disaster recovery agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongala.
The tsunami struck the western part of the Dongala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic “Pacific Ring of Fire” and is regularly affected by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on December 26 on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in North Sumatra triggered a wave of tsunamis that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people across the entire coastline of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude quake hit Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that crashed into the south coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake strikes near the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake hit one of the Mentaway Islands and triggered a 10-metre wave of tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Paddy Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastation from the deadly earthquake and tsunami in 2004.
There was no tsunami this time, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Heavy quakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, most of them from the northern side of the island.
