New to the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinelas, Manuti and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Committee shows a substantial reduction in red tidal concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there have been reports of growth disruption in the Pinelas, Manuti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – this indicates a decrease in concentrations.
Excessively blooming red tide watersheds stretch for approximately 130 miles along the coast, from northern Pinelas County to southern Lee County.
Algae patches can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsboro County, but are smaller than last week.
A red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly more inland in the Pinelas county, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough county, high concentrations in the Manuti county, high concentrations in the coastal county, or high concentrations in the coastal county.
Inflammation of the respiratory tract continues to be reported in Pinelas, Manuti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of airway inflammation in Northwest Florida over the past week.
